    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-03-12T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-03-12T18:00:00-05:00" n="746"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d746">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.5212A/7: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hammond</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-03-12T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 12, 1928—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. The Department handed the Spanish Ambassador on March 12, a draft of a
                    proposed Treaty of Arbitration between the United States and Spain. The
                    provisions of the draft operate to extend the policy of arbitration enunciated
                    in the Root Treaty of April 20, 1908, which expired June 2, 1923. The language
                    of the draft is identical in effect with that of the arbitration treaty recently
                    signed with France and with the draft arbitration treaties already submitted to
                    the Norwegian, British, Japanese, Italian and German Governments.<note n="54"
                        xml:id="d746fn54">For negotiations with Germany and Great Britain, see <ref
                            target="frus1928v02#pg_862">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, pp.
                            862</ref> ff., and <ref target="frus1928v02#pg_943">pp. 943</ref> ff.;
                        with Italy and Japan, see <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_102"
                            >pp. 102</ref> ff. and <ref target="#pg_135">pp. 135</ref> ff. Although
                        negotiations with Norway were instituted in 1928, the treaty was not signed
                        until 1929 (Department of State Treaty Series No. 788).</note> The text of
                    the proposed treaty will be forwarded in the next pouch.<note n="55"
                        xml:id="d746fn55">Draft treaty not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
